<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-415-335  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 415 335.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Sept 10 1990 n607 p54(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Boundary scan is not enough. (most board-level testing alsorequires in-circuit testing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hansen, Peter; Rosenblatt, Carl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Most board-level circuit testing requires a mix of boundary-scanand in-circuit testing strategies since most boards combineboundary-scan and conventional components.andP;  The creation of atestable circuit board involves the utilization of boundary-scancomponents where possible and analysis of non-scan portions of adesign for possible in-circuit testability problems.andP;  Severalkinds of design analysis facilitate the testing of complex boarddesigns, including the use of expert-system-based approaches.andO;Circuit data required for testability analysis include adescription of the circuit, typically as a net-list output form acomputer-aided design system, and detailed descriptions of eachcomponent.andP;  Details of the design and functioning of in-circuittesters in analyzing the viability of a device under test (DUT)are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     On-Board SystemsTestingTest EquipmentFailure AnalysisCircuit QualityBoards-CardsSystems Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Interconnect testing; virtual in-circuit testing. (chart)Loops can be subtle. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>